04720nam a22006615i 9780748610839DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20221999stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486108397 a10.1515/97807486108392doi  a(DE-B1597)616057  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a306.44  aER 9902rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27788:1 aChouliaraki, Lilie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiscourse in Late Modernity :bRethinking Critical Discourse Analysis /cLilie Chouliaraki, Norman Fairclough. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Discourse Analysis : CDA00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tSeries Preface -- t1 Discourse in late modernity -- t2 Social life and critical social science -- t3 Discourse -- t4 The critical analysis of discourse -- t5 Narratives o f late modernity and a research agenda for CDA -- t6 Language, space and time -- t7 Discourse, difference and the openness of the social -- t8 Critical discourse analysis and linguistics -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDiscourse in Late Modernity sets out to show that critical discourse analysis is strongly positioned to address empirical research and theory-building across the social sciences, particularly research and theory on the semiotic/linguistic aspects of the social world. It situates critical discourse analysis as a form of critical social research in relation to diverse theories from the philosophy of science to social theory and from political science to sociology and linguistics. First, the authors clarify the ontological and epistemological assumptions of critical discourse analysis - its view of what the social world consists of and how to study it - and, in so doing, point to the connections between critical discourse analysis and critical social scientific research more generally. Secondly, they relate critical discourse analysis to social theory, by creating a research agenda in contemporary social life on the basis of narratives of late modernity, particularly those of Giddens, Habermas, and Harvey as well as feminist and postmodernist approaches. Thirdly, they show the relevance of sociological work in the analysis of discursive aspects of social life, drawing on the work of Bourdieu and Bernstein to theorise the dialectic of social reproduction and change, and on post-structuralist, post-colonial and feminist work to theorise the dialectic of complexity and homogenisation in contemporary societies. Finally, they discuss the relationship between systemic-functional linguistics and critical discourse analysis, showing how the analytical strength of each can benefit from the other.Sets out a new and distinctive theoretical grounding and research agenda for critical discourse analysisInterdisciplinary in scopeDraws on a broad range of theories and approaches  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aFairclough, Norman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311078047540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074861083940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748610839423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748610839/original  a978-3-11-078047-5  Edinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  